 <!-- MODULE 2: FINGERSTICK -->
 <div class="page" id="page-mod3">
 <div class="module-header">
 <div class="module-tag">Module 03</div>
 <h2>Fingerstick SOP</h2>
 <div class="desc">USW Capillary Collection Method — standard operating procedure for all blood-draw screening events.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="callout warn">
 <span class="callout-icon">📋</span>
 <div><strong>Consent &amp; Forms</strong> Participants who made an appointment in advance signed the consent form online. If no appointment, the consent form will appear in the Salesforce app for you to complete. If using paper, always get a signed consent — paper forms are in your shipment. You keep the white copy; give the participant the yellow copy. Keep completed forms face down at your station.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="section-title">Required Supplies</div>
 <div class="two-col">
 <div class="info-card">
 <div class="card-title">Consumables per Participant</div>
 <ul class="bullet-list" style="margin-top:8px">
 <li>Test strips (fasting or non-fasting) + glucose strips</li>
 <li>Alcohol pad</li>
 <li>Gauze pads (×2+)</li>
 <li>Lancet (one-time use)</li>
 <li>Bandage</li>
 <li>Capillary tube</li>
 </ul>
 </div>
 <div class="info-card">
 <div class="card-title">Key Rules</div>
 <ul class="bullet-list" style="margin-top:8px">
 <li>Change gloves between every participant</li>
 <li>Wipe away the first drop of blood</li>
 <li>Fill capillary tube within 10 seconds</li>
 <li>Never touch capillary tube to skin</li>
 <li>All lancets into Sharps container immediately</li>
 </ul>
 </div>
 </div>

 <div class="section-title">Standard Operating Procedure</div>
 <ol class="sop-list">
 <li>Verify participant's full name and date of birth.</li>
 <li>Complete any Q&amp;A presented in Salesforce.</li>
 <li>Sanitize hands and apply latex-free gloves. The participant should witness you putting them on.</li>
 <li>Open sterile packaging in the presence of the participant.</li>
 <li>Check for temperature and blood flow to the fingertip — if hands are cold, have them rub vigorously together while you set up.</li>
 <li>Select the ring or middle finger of the non-dominant hand. Use the outer edge of the finger facing you, not the tip, not calloused skin, not the fleshy padded area.</li>
 <li>Clean the selected finger with an alcohol pad. Let dry.</li>
 <li>Place the lancet firmly on the finger then press the trigger. Dispose of the lancet in the Sharps container.</li>
 <li>Wipe away the first drop of blood with a gauze pad.</li>
 <li>Squeeze the finger at the knuckle nearest the fingertip until a bead of blood forms. Hold the capillary tube horizontally to the fingertip. Fill to the black line within 10 seconds. Do not touch the tube to the skin or scrape the skin with the tube.</li>
 <li>Once the tube is full, place gauze over the puncture site and ask the participant to hold pressure.</li>
 <li>Apply bandage to the participant's finger. All participants must be bandaged before leaving the station.</li>
 </ol>

 <div class="section-title">Re-stick Policy</div>
 <div class="two-col">
 <div class="do-box">
 <h5>✓ Allowed</h5>
 <ul>
 <li>Re-stick if needed to obtain a valid blood sample (e.g., insufficient sample, equipment issue)</li>
 <li>Re-stick if a reaction does not occur during collection</li>
 </ul>
 </div>
 <div class="dont-box">
 <h5>✗ Not Allowed</h5>
 <ul>
 <li>Re-stick because the participant is dissatisfied with their result</li>
 <li>Re-run a test to try to get a different number</li>
 </ul>
 </div>
 </div>

 <div class="section-title">Insufficient Sample — Common Causes</div>
 <ul class="bullet-list">
 <li><strong>Dehydration</strong> — the most common cause. Dehydrated blood is more viscous and harder to flow.</li>
 <li><strong>Poor technique</strong> — selecting a calloused finger, taking more than 10 seconds to fill the tube, inadequate sample, or "milking" the finger.</li>
 <li><strong>Poor circulation</strong> — cold hands reduce blood flow.</li>
 <li><strong>Medication</strong> — some medications affect blood flow or clotting.</li>
 </ul>

 <div class="section-title">Participant Safety Considerations</div>
 <ul class="bullet-list">
 <li><strong>Needle/blood aversion:</strong> Do not ask about this proactively. If the participant brings it up, be empathetic and supportive and observe them throughout the process.</li>
 <li><strong>Fainting:</strong> If a physical reaction occurs during or after specimen collection, follow your emergency guidelines and the client's policy for emergencies.</li>
 <li>All participants must have a bandage applied before leaving the fingerstick station.</li>
 </ul>

