 <!-- MODULE 5a: BLOOD PRESSURE -->
 <div class="page" id="page-mod7">
 <div class="module-header">
 <div class="module-tag">Module 07</div>
 <h2>Blood Pressure</h2>
 <div class="desc">Manual blood pressure screening procedure, thresholds, and emergency protocols.</div>
 </div>

 <p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:14px">Blood pressure is PHI — never read results aloud. Point to the recorded value on the results form. Use USW-provided cuffs and sphygmomanometer (you may use your own stethoscope with manager approval).</p>

 <ol class="sop-list">
 <li>Set up table and chair so the participant's <strong>left arm</strong> is accessible. Feet flat on the floor.</li>
 <li>Have the participant sit down, remain calm, quiet, and breathe normally. Explain the procedure.</li>
 <li>Have them remove outer clothing (coat, sweater) if possible. Skin-to-cuff contact is preferred.</li>
 <li>Select appropriate cuff size using the parameters printed inside the cuff.</li>
 <li>Position forearm resting on the surface, <strong>palm facing up</strong>, artery level with the heart.</li>
 <li>Place cuff snugly on the left arm, ½ to 1 inch above the elbow crease.</li>
 <li>Place stethoscope earpieces slightly forward. Place the diaphragm/bell over the brachial artery, just above and inside the elbow crease.</li>
 <li>Inflate to 180–200 mmHg. Slowly release the valve.</li>
 <li>Note the gauge reading at the first tapping sound (systolic). Note the last tap (diastolic).</li>
 <li>Record blood pressure on the results sheet and enter into the tablet.</li>
 </ol>

 <div class="two-col">
 <div class="info-card">
 <div class="card-title">Re-check Threshold</div>
 <div class="card-val">140/90</div>
 <p>Perform a second manual blood pressure reading if the first result is at or above this level.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="info-card">
 <div class="card-title">Emergency Report Threshold</div>
 <div class="card-val" style="color:var(--usw-danger)">180/100</div>
 <p>If second reading is 180/100 or greater, submit a Medical Emergency Report and call 866.881.7607.</p>
 </div>
 </div>

 <div class="callout danger">
 <span class="callout-icon">🚑</span>
 <div><strong>High BP Emergency Care</strong> If participant reads 180/100+ and presents severe headache, blurred vision, dizziness/drowsiness, or chest pain: advise they are in the "significantly high" range, complete a medical referral form, encourage immediate medical follow-up, and if symptoms are severe consider calling an ambulance. Call 866.881.7607 right away.</div>
 </div>

