 <!-- MODULE 5b: WAIST CIRCUMFERENCE -->
 <div class="page" id="page-mod8">
 <div class="module-header">
 <div class="module-tag">Module 08</div>
 <h2>Waist Circumference</h2>
 <div class="desc">How to measure and record waist circumference accurately and sensitively.</div>
 </div>

 <ol class="sop-list">
 <li>Ask the participant to stand upright and explain that you are going to take a quick waist measurement at their natural waist. Be sensitive to any anxiety the participant may be feeling about this measurement. Set them at ease.</li>
 <li>Position the tape measure at the natural waist, the narrowest part of the torso, typically located just above your belly button and below the ribcage.</li>
 <li>For sanitary reasons, measurements are preferred over clothing — not directly on skin.</li>
 <li>You may have the participant hold the tape and turn around to avoid reaching around them.</li>
 <li>Make sure the tape is snug but not too tight.</li>
 <li>Record to the nearest ½ inch. Round down to account for clothing.</li>
 <li>If asked for their result, point to the recorded value — never say it aloud.</li>
 </ol>

 <div class="two-col">
 <div class="info-card">
 <div class="card-title">Goal — Female</div>
 <div class="card-val">&lt; 35 inches</div>
 <p>Excess abdominal fat increases risk of Type II diabetes, hypertension, and heart disease. A 5cm (~2 inch) reduction can significantly reduce risk.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="info-card">
 <div class="card-title">Goal — Male</div>
 <div class="card-val">&lt; 40 inches</div>
 <p>Measure at the natural curve of the waist, just above the belly button, parallel to the floor.</p>
 </div>
 </div>

