 <div class="section-title">Counseling Principles</div>
 <p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:12px">Counseling on results is the biggest value we offer to clients. Some participants have limited understanding of their results; others are well informed and expect you to validate what they already know. Either way, it's your job to rise to their level and offer a meaningful overview of their results.</p>
 <ul class="bullet-list">
 <li><strong>How you show up matters.</strong> Be open, approachable, and invested in their experience. Smile. Above all else, keep it private.</li>
 <li><strong>Adjust to the needs of each participant</strong> — not everyone requires the same depth of explanation. Read the room.</li>
 <li><strong>Never say results aloud</strong> where others can hear — always point to the value on the form. This is PHI.</li>
 <li><strong>Be open to questions and feedback</strong> — participants may have concerns; listen and respond appropriately.</li>
 <li><strong>You have the power</strong> to help people leave this experience pleased and informed. Make it a great one.</li>
 </ul>

 <div class="callout warn">
 <span class="callout-icon">⚠️</span>
 <div><strong>Scope of practice reminder</strong> Screeners provide health education — not medical advice. For any result outside of normal range, advise participants to follow up with their physician and refer them to resources included in your event materials.</div>
 </div>

 <h3 class="sub">Waist Circumference</h3>
 <p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:12px">You can discuss the goal measurement out loud, but <strong>never give the participant their actual measurement aloud</strong> — just point to it on the results form.</p>
 <ul class="bullet-list">
 <li>US national standards recommend &lt;35 inches for women and &lt;40 inches for men. Excess abdominal fat closely correlates with risk of Type II diabetes, hypertension, and heart disease.</li>
 <li>Not everyone identifies as male or female — respect that. If you sense the participant may not want gendered guidelines, simply say: "Our goal is about 35–40 inches and yours is here" and point to the result.</li>
 </ul>

 <h3 class="sub">BMI</h3>
 <p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:12px">BMI uses height and weight to give an indicator of overall healthy weight. It is not perfect — it does not account for muscle mass, bone density, or every body's natural unique shapes. Use it carefully, as it is often incorporated into wellness rewards and incentives.</p>
 <ul class="bullet-list">
 <li>Goal range: <strong>18.5–24.9</strong>. Each point on the BMI scale equals approximately 5 lbs.</li>
 <li>Many people's BMI is higher than this due to muscle mass or other factors — counsel with sensitivity.</li>
 </ul>

 <h3 class="sub">Blood Pressure</h3>
 <p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:12px">High blood pressure can damage vessels and organs — often with no symptoms until serious problems like heart attack or stroke occur. It's measured in two numbers: systolic (top, heart beats) and diastolic (bottom, heart rests). Goal: &lt;120/80 mmHg.</p>
 <ul class="bullet-list">
 <li>If BP is &gt;140/90, discreetly point to the result and say: "Your BP is here today. The goal is below 120/80. Since high blood pressure doesn't always show symptoms, it's important to check it regularly at your doctor or pharmacy and talk to your doctor if it's high." Make eye contact, nod, and ensure the message settles in.</li>
 <li>If BP is in the red zone (≥180/100), look for symptoms: anxiety, blurred vision, headache, shortness of breath. Ask "How are you feeling today?" Encourage them to see their doctor. If symptoms are present, call US Wellness on-call at <strong>866.881.7607</strong> and complete a Medical Emergency Report. You will find a button for the medical emergency form on the data entry record in Salesforce. If your event uses OPA, complete a paper form.</li>
 </ul>

 <h3 class="sub">Cholesterol</h3>
 <p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:12px">Cholesterol is an essential fat found in the blood. Our body needs it, but too much can build up on artery walls or weaken arteries. Be careful about using the word "fat" — some participants focus on it and think you're calling them fat. Clarify if needed.</p>
 <ul class="bullet-list">
 <li><strong>Total Cholesterol</strong> goal: &lt;200 mg/dL. A 5–10% variability is acceptable — do not retest cholesterol unless you receive an error reading, as variability can confuse participants.</li>
 <li><strong>HDL ("good cholesterol")</strong> — the only number we want to be high. Goal: &gt;40 mg/dL for men, &gt;50 mg/dL for women. HDL acts as a cleanser, transporting LDL to the liver for removal. Improved by olive oil, fish, nuts, and reducing animal fats and packaged foods.</li>
 <li><strong>LDL ("bad cholesterol")</strong> — a <em>calculated</em> value using TC, HDL, and Triglycerides. Goal: &lt;100 mg/dL. If LDL reads N/A, it means the HDL or triglycerides are extremely high or low and the calculation cannot be completed — this does not mean LDL is abnormal. Explain this to the participant.</li>
 <li><strong>TC/HDL Ratio</strong> — total cholesterol divided by HDL. Goal: &lt;5.0. This is a reliable counseling anchor because it balances variability in TC.</li>
 <li><strong>Triglycerides</strong> goal: &lt;150 mg/dL. When the body doesn't burn the energy from food, it converts it to triglycerides stored in fat cells. Energy balance — eating appropriately, regular activity, and adequate sleep — is key to managing triglycerides.</li>
 </ul>

 <div class="callout info">
 <span class="callout-icon">💡</span>
 <div><strong>Pro Tip — TC=400 / HDL=100:</strong> If you get a TC of 400 and HDL of 100, this is the one circumstance where you should retest. This result is likely user error — a dirty CardioChek glass or a backwards strip. In very rare cases, highly viscous blood may cause issues; suggest a venous blood draw at their doctor's office.</div>
 </div>

 <h3 class="sub">Glucose &amp; HbA1c</h3>
 <p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:12px">Glucose and triglycerides are closely correlated — both depend on how the body uses energy from food. Over time, high glucose causes permanent damage to veins and arteries and can lead to insulin resistance and diabetes. Goal for fasting glucose: &lt;100 mg/dL.</p>
 <ul class="bullet-list">
 <li><strong>HbA1c</strong> reflects average blood glucose over the last 2–3 months. High A1c over time increases risk of stroke, heart attack, and diabetes.</li>
 <li>Burning energy through exercise, eating foods low in sugar and high in fiber and protein, and getting enough rest can all help improve glucose levels.</li>
 </ul>

 <div class="section-title">Full Reference Table</div>
 <table class="ref-table">
 <thead><tr><th>Measurement</th><th>Goal / Normal</th><th>Counseling Note</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>HbA1c</td><td><span class="tag-normal">≤ 5.6%</span></td><td>Normal; reinforce healthy habits</td></tr>
 <tr><td>HbA1c</td><td><span class="tag-warn">5.7–6.4%</span></td><td>Pre-diabetes risk; lifestyle counseling + physician follow-up</td></tr>
 <tr><td>HbA1c</td><td><span class="tag-danger">≥ 6.5%</span></td><td>Diabetes range; provide pamphlet + refer to physician</td></tr>
