 <!-- MODULE 14: MEDICAL EMERGENCY PROTOCOL -->
 <div class="page" id="page-mod15">
 <div class="module-header">
 <div class="module-tag">Module 15</div>
 <h2>Medical Emergency Protocol</h2>
 <div class="desc">Immediate response procedures for medical emergencies, fainting, bleeding, and critical screening results at US Wellness events.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="callout danger">
 <span class="callout-icon">🚨</span>
 <div><strong>Emergency? Call 911 first.</strong> Then contact USW on-call at <strong>(866) 881-7607</strong> immediately following the emergency.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="section-title">Immediate Response — Any Medical Emergency</div>
 <p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:10px">In the event of a medical emergency, USW personnel or contractors on-site will <strong>immediately</strong>:</p>
 <ul class="bullet-list">
 <li>Discontinue any screening processes.</li>
 <li>Assess the situation and call 911 if there is a need for immediate medical attention.</li>
 <li>Assist the participant to ensure they are comfortable and relaxed.</li>
 <li>Maintain continuous participant supervision until all symptoms subside, the participant is stable, or they are transported to a medical facility.</li>
 <li>Call USW at <strong>(866) 881-7607</strong> immediately following the emergency to report the incident.</li>
 <li>At the first possible moment, document all details on the <strong>US Wellness Medical Emergency Report Form</strong> (found in the brown expandable folder in your event shipment). Document: date, time, location; full description of the emergency; any notable verbal communications; full description of how the emergency was managed, who was called, and how it was resolved.</li>
 </ul>

 <div class="section-title">Fainting Protocol</div>
 <p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:10px">While waiting for 911 emergency personnel to arrive:</p>
 <ul class="bullet-list">
 <li>Position the person on their back. If breathing, raise legs about 12 inches above heart level to restore blood flow to the brain. Loosen belts, collars, or other constrictive clothing. Do not get the person up too quickly.</li>
 <li>Check the airway to ensure it is clear. Watch for vomiting.</li>
 <li>Recheck BP and glucose.</li>
 <li>Check for signs of circulation (breathing, coughing, or movement). If absent, begin CPR and continue until help arrives or the person responds and begins to breathe.</li>
 <li>If the person was injured in a fall, treat any bumps, bruises, or cuts appropriately. Control bleeding with direct pressure.</li>
 </ul>

 <div class="section-title">Excessive Bleeding Protocol</div>
 <p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:10px">While waiting for 911 emergency personnel to arrive:</p>
 <ul class="bullet-list">
 <li>Have the individual apply direct pressure on the wound using a sterile bandage or clean cloth. Hold continuous pressure for at least 20 minutes without checking whether bleeding has stopped. Bind the wound tightly with a bandage and adhesive tape. Use gloves or a clean plastic bag for protection if available.</li>
 <li>Do not remove the gauze or bandage. If bleeding continues and seeps through, add more absorbent material on top — do not remove the original dressing. Wait for emergency personnel to arrive.</li>
 </ul>

 <div class="section-title">Critical Screening Results — When to Act</div>
 <p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:10px">Initiate participant management response for any of the following:</p>
 <ul class="bullet-list">
 <li>Blood pressure &gt;180/100 mmHg</li>
 <li>Fasting glucose &gt;200 mg/dL</li>
 <li>Non-fasting glucose &gt;300 mg/dL</li>
 <li>Fasting or non-fasting glucose &lt;70 mg/dL</li>
 </ul>

 <div class="two-col">
 <div class="info-card">
 <div class="card-title">No Symptoms Present</div>
 <p>Inform the participant their reading is in a "significantly high" range. Recommend they notify their physician and follow their recommended action plan.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="info-card">
 <div class="card-title" style="color:var(--usw-danger)">Symptoms Present</div>
 <p>Severe headache · Blurred vision · Dizziness or drowsiness · Chest pain · Sweating · Nausea/vomiting · Shortness of breath · Fatigue, confusion, or anxiety</p>
 </div>
 </div>

 <div class="section-title">Procedure When Symptoms Are Present</div>
 <ol class="sop-list">
 <li>Ensure the participant is seated.</li>
 <li>Inform them their reading is in a "significantly high" range and that their symptoms may indicate an acute episode requiring medical attention.</li>
 <li>Work with another USW team member to maintain oversight at all times. If alone, request support from the site. The individual must not return to work or leave the site alone.</li>
 <li>Contact USW on-call at <strong>(866) 881-7607</strong> as soon as possible. USW on-call medical personnel can help support decisions regarding emergency medical services and immediate treatment.</li>
 <li>Complete the Medical Emergency Report on the USW tablet (appointment summary page) — it is tied to the patient's record. Provide as much detail as possible. Phone number is required. If your event uses OPA, complete the paper form.</li>
 <li><strong>911 Protocol:</strong>
 <ul style="margin-top:8px;padding-left:16px;list-style:disc;">
 <li>Take all possible steps to create calm and manage the situation.</li>
 <li>Protect the participant's PHI except for necessary disclosure to 911 personnel.</li>
 <li>Inform the participant you are calling an ambulance for further evaluation, then call 911.</li>
 <li>Be prepared to provide 911 personnel with the participant's results, symptoms, age, gender, and other pertinent details.</li>
 <li>If the participant refuses transport, that is their right — but they must refuse care to emergency medical personnel directly, not to a USW team member or site contact.</li>
 <li>If the participant is transported, update the USW on-call team at <strong>(866) 881-7607</strong> and complete the medical emergency form. Protect PHI in all interactions at the site.</li>
 </ul>
 </li>
 </ol>

